TH man 1 "22 - Feb 23" "0.1" "simple_shell man page"

.SH NAME
simple_shell - A simple shell program in C for interacting with a Linux operating system.

.SH SYNOPSIS
hsh [options] [file]

.SH DESCRIPTION
The term "shell" refers to the user interface with an operating system that interprets and executes user commands. The simple_shell program reads and interprets commands from a file or the terminal, and executes them. It is typically launched automatically when a user logs in to the system. Simple_shell supports both interactive and non-interactive use, such as shell scripts. The program will search for executables in all directories listed in the PATH environment variable. The return value for successful execution is always 0.

.SH OVERVIEW
The simple_shell program is a command that reads lines from either a file or the terminal, interprets them, and generally executes other commands. It incorporates many features to aid interactive use, and its interpretive language is common to both interactive and non-interactive use. Commands can be typed directly into the running simple_shell or can be placed in a file and executed directly by the program.

.SH RETURN VALUE
The return value for successful execution is always 0. A non-zero value indicates a failure.

.SH OPTIONS
Command options can be entered after the main command followed by a space and a '-' symbol.

.SH EXAMPLE
For example, to list files and directories with additional information, the command would be:
$ ls -l

.SH BUGS
A single space is required after each argument.

.SH AUTHOR
The simple_shell program was created by Daniel and Ahmed.
